-- S.Korean shares edge higher on bargain-hunting; won rebounds from 6-month low
-- By Joonhee Yu
-- Tue Oct 07, 2014 02:13AM EDT
-- None



SEOUL, Oct 7 (Reuters) - South Korean shares edged higher on Tuesday, snapping a seven-day losing streak as bargain hunters locked in on recently battered stocks.

The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) <.KS11> gained 0.23 percent to close at 1,972.91 points. The South Korean won <KRW=> firmed against the dollar on short-covering after dipping to a fresh six-month low against the greenback in the previous session.